    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The inductive reactance ($X_L$) is not a fixed opposition like a simple resistor; it actually changes with the frequency of the AC source. It is directly proportional to the frequency ($X_L = 2\\pi fL$), meaning if you change the frequency, the inductor's resistance to current flow changes too. Unlike a resistor that always offers its set resistance, the inductor's opposition is dynamic, depending on how fast the current is trying to change. This is why we must use impedance, which accounts for this frequency-dependent behavior.",
      "source": "target",
